{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649330"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:03:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:03:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18357"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18357"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.27,0.09,0.55,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11075"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74358"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11075"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59849"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7472"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25688"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25691"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74358"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is the most posterior in the tarsal tunnel?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tibial artery and veins","Tibialis posterior","Tibial nerve","Flexor hallucis longus","Flexor digitorum longus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe tarsal tunnel is a narrow space on the medial side of the ankle, formed by the flexor retinaculum. It contains several important structures that pass from the leg into the foot. The order of these structures from anterior to posterior is often remembered by the mnemonic \u0027Tom, Dick, and A Very Nervous Harry\u0027: \u003Cstrong\u003ETibialis posterior\u003C/strong\u003E (Tom), \u003Cstrong\u003EFlexor digitorum longus\u003C/strong\u003E (Dick), \u003Cstrong\u003ETibial artery and veins\u003C/strong\u003E (A), \u003Cstrong\u003ETibial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (Very Nervous), and \u003Cstrong\u003EFlexor hallucis longus\u003C/strong\u003E (Harry).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexor hallucis longus\u003C/strong\u003E is the most posterior structure in the tarsal tunnel. It is important to understand this arrangement for diagnosing conditions such as tarsal tunnel syndrome, where compression of the tibial nerve can lead to pain and tingling in the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETibial artery and veins\u003C/strong\u003E are located anterior to the tibial nerve and flexor hallucis longus, making them less posterior.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETibialis posterior\u003C/strong\u003E is the most anterior structure in the tarsal tunnel, not the most posterior.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETibial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is located anterior to the flexor hallucis longus, making it less posterior.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexor digitorum longus\u003C/strong\u003E is located anterior to the tibial artery and veins, tibial nerve, and flexor hallucis longus, making it less posterior.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The flexor hallucis longus tendon is the most posterior structure in the tarsal tunnel.","Understanding the order of structures in the tarsal tunnel is important for diagnosing and managing conditions like tarsal tunnel syndrome."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59849"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18357"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59849"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T04:54:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T04:54:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11075"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74358"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonym